<exercise><title><fromexam>M200 2016D</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
<ol label="a">
<li><p>
Some level curves of a function <m>f(x,y)</m> are plotted in the <m>xy</m>--plane
below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="75%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE16D_2a"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
For each of the four statements below, circle the letters of
<alert>all</alert> points in the diagram where the situation applies.
For example, if the statement were <q>These points are on the <m>y</m>--axis</q>, you would circle both <m>P</m> and <m>U</m>, but none of the other letters.
You may assume that a local maximum occurs at point <m>T</m>.
<md>
<mrow>
\text{(i) }&amp; \vnabla f\text{ is zero} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
</mrow><mrow>
\text{(ii) }&amp; f \text{ has a saddle point} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
</mrow><mrow>
\text{(iii) }&amp; \text{ the partial derivative $f_y$ is positive} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
</mrow><mrow>
\text{(iv) }&amp; \text{ the directional derivative of $f$ in the
                 direction $\llt 0,-1\rgt$ is} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
</mrow><mrow>
          &amp; \text{ negative} &amp; &amp;
</mrow>
</md>
</p></li>
<li><p>
The diagram below shows three <q><m>y</m> traces</q> of a graph <m>z=F(x,y)</m> plotted
on <m>xz</m>--axes. (Namely the intersections of the surface  <m>z=F(x,y)</m> with the
three planes (<m>y=1.9</m>, <m>y=2</m>, <m>y=2.1</m>). For each statement below, circle the
correct word.
<md>
<mrow>
\text{(i) }&amp; \text{ the first order partial derivative $F_x(1,2)$ is} &amp; &amp;
\text{positive/negative/zero}
</mrow><mrow>
\text{(ii) }&amp; F \text{ has a critical point at } (2,2) &amp;
         &amp;\text{true/false}
</mrow><mrow>
\text{(iii) }&amp; \text{ the second order partial derivative $F_{xy}(1,2)$ is} &amp; &amp;\text{positive/negative/zero}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
<sidebyside width="66%">
  <image source="pfigs/OE16D_2b"/>
</sidebyside>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) (i) <m>T</m>, <m>U</m>
</p>

<p>(a) (ii) <m>U</m>
</p>

<p>(a) (iii) <m>S</m>
</p>

<p>(a) (iv) <m>S</m>
</p>

<p>(b) (i) <m>F_x(1,2) \gt 0</m>
</p>

<p>(b) (ii) <m>F</m> does <em>not</em> have a critical point at <m>(2,2)</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) (iii) <m>F_{xy}(1,2) \lt 0</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
a) (i) <m>\vnabla f</m> is zero at critical points.
        The point <m>T</m> is a local maximum and the point <m>U</m> is
        a saddle point. The remaining points <m>P</m>, <m>R</m>, <m>S</m>, are not
        critical points.
</p>

<p>(a) (ii) Only <m>U</m> is a saddle point.
</p>

<p>(a) (iii) We have <m>f_y(x,y) \gt 0</m> if <m>f</m> increases as you move vertically upward
          through <m>(x,y)</m>. Looking at the diagram, we see
<md>
<mrow>
f_y(P)  &amp;\lt 0&amp;
f_y(Q)  &amp;\lt 0&amp;
f_y(R) &amp;=0</mrow><mrow>
f_y(S)  &amp;\gt 0&amp;
f_y(T) &amp;=0&amp;
f_y(U) &amp;=0
</mrow>
</md>
So only <m>S</m> works.
</p>

<p>(a) (iv) The directional derivative of <m>f</m> in the direction <m>\llt 0,-1\rgt</m>
           is <m>\vnabla f\cdot \llt 0,-1\rgt =-f_y</m>. It is negative if and
           only if <m>f_y \gt 0</m>. So, again, only <m>S</m> works.
</p>

<p>(b) (i) The function <m>z=F(x,2)</m> is increasing at <m>x=1</m>,
     because the <m>y=2.0</m> graph in the diagram has positive slope at <m>x=1</m>.
     So <m>F_x(1,2) \gt 0</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) (ii) The function <m>z=F(x,2)</m> is also increasing (though slowly) at <m>x=2</m>,
     because the <m>y=2.0</m> graph in the diagram has positive slope at <m>x=2</m>.
     So <m>F_x(2,2) \gt 0</m>. So <m>F</m> does <em>not</em> have a critical point
     at <m>(2,2)</m>.
</p>

<p>(b) (iii) From the diagram the looks like
                <m>F_x(1,1.9)  \gt  F_x(1,2.0)  \gt  F_x(1,2.1)</m>.
      That is, it looks like the slope of the <m>y=1.9</m> graph at <m>x=1</m>
             is larger than the slope of the <m>y=2.0</m> graph at <m>x=1</m>,
             which in turn
             is larger than the slope of the <m>y=2.1</m> graph at <m>x=1</m>.
     So it looks like <m>F_x(1,y)</m> decreases as <m>y</m> increases through <m>y=2</m>,
     and consequently <m>F_{xy}(1,2) \lt 0</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Find the high and low points of the surface <m>\ z=\sqrt{x^2+y^2}\ </m> with <m>(x,y)</m>
varying over the square <m>\ |x|\le 1</m>, <m>|y|\le 1\ </m>. Discuss the values of
<m>\ z_x,\ z_y\ </m> there. Do not evaluate any derivatives in answering this
question.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Interpret the height <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> geometrically.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
The minimum height is zero at <m>(0,0,0)</m>. The derivatives
<m>z_x</m> and <m>z_y</m> do not exist there.
The maximum height is <m>\sqrt{2}</m> at <m>(\pm 1,\pm 1,\sqrt{2})</m>.
There <m>z_x</m> and <m>z_y</m> exist but are not zero <mdash/> those points would
not be the highest points if it were not for the restriction
<m>|x|,|y|\le 1</m>.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
The height <m>\sqrt{x^2+y^2}</m> at <m>(x,y)</m> is the distance from <m>(x,y)</m>
to <m>(0,0)</m>. So the minimum height is zero at <m>(0,0,0)</m>. The surface is a
cone. The cone has a point at <m>(0,0,0)</m> and the derivatives
<m>z_x</m> and <m>z_y</m> do not exist there.
The maximum height is achieved when <m>(x,y)</m> is as far as possible from
<m>(0,0)</m>. The highest points are at <m>(\pm 1,\pm 1,\sqrt{2})</m>. There
<m>z_x</m> and <m>z_y</m> exist but are not zero. These points would not
be the highest points if it were not for the restriction <m>|x|,|y|\le 1</m>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
If <m>t_0</m> is a local minimum or maximum of the smooth function <m>\ f(t)\ </m>
of one variable (<m>t</m> runs over all real numbers) then <m>\ f'(t_0)=0.</m>
Derive an analogous necessary condition for <m>\vx_0</m> to be a local minimum
or maximium of the smooth function <m>\ g(\vx)\ </m> <alert>restricted</alert> to points on
the line <m>\ \vx=\va+t\vd\ .</m> The test should involve the gradient
of <m>g(\vx)</m>.
</p>

</statement>

<hint><p>
Define <m>f(t)=g(\va+t\vd)</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
<m>\vnabla g(\vx_0)\cdot\vd=0</m>, i.e. <m>\vnabla g(\vx_0)\perp\vd</m>, and <m>\vx_0=\va+t_0\vd</m> for some <m>t_0</m>.
The second condition is to ensure that <m>x_0</m> lies on the line.
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
 Define <m>f(t)=g(\va+t\vd)</m> and determine <m>t_0</m> by
<m>\vx_0=\va+t_0\vd</m>. Then <m>f'(t)=\vnabla g(\va+t\vd)\cdot\vd</m>.
To see this, write <m>\va=\llt a_1,a_2,a_3\rgt</m> and <m>\vd=\llt d_1,d_2,d_3\rgt</m>.
Then
<me>
f(t)=g(a_1+td_1,a_2+td_2,a_3+td_3)
</me>
So, by the chain rule,
<md>
<mrow>
f'(t) &amp;= \pdiff{g}{x}(a_1+td_1,a_2+td_2,a_3+td_3)\,d_1
</mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1in
       +\pdiff{g}{y}(a_1+td_1,a_2+td_2,a_3+td_3)\,d_2
</mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip1in
       +\pdiff{g}{z}(a_1+td_1,a_2+td_2,a_3+td_3)\,d_3
</mrow><mrow>
     &amp;=\vnabla g(\va+t\vd)\cdot\vd
</mrow>
</md>
Then <m>\vx_0</m> is a local
max or min of the restriction of <m>g</m>  to the specified line if and only
if <m>t_0</m> is a local max or min of <m>f(t)</m>. If so, <m>f'(t_0)</m>  necessarily
vanishes. So if <m>\vx_0</m> is a local
max or min of the restriction of <m>g</m>  to the specified line,
then <m>\vnabla g(\vx_0)\cdot\vd=0</m>, i.e. <m>\vnabla g(\vx_0)\perp\vd</m>, and <m>\vx_0=\va+t_0\vd</m> for some <m>t_0</m>.
The second condition is to ensure that <m>x_0</m> lies on the line.
</p></solution>
</exercise>
